pouch boundary-line patch 0021 - the POSIX pty surface (PTY-3).

PTY-DESIGN.md section 7. Makes the POSIX pseudoterminal + job-control
surface work for ported programs over the PTY-1 kernel syscalls + the
PTY-2 ptyfs server, WITHOUT any new kernel surface: openpty /
posix_openpt / grantpt / unlockpt / ptsname_r / isatty / tcgetattr /
tcsetattr / tcgetpgrp / tcsetpgrp / tcgetwinsize / tcsetwinsize /
setsid / setpgid / getpgid / getsid + the tty signal family
(SIGQUIT / SIGTSTP / SIGCONT / SIGWINCH / SIGHUP <-> tty:*).

Sixteen files:

  arch/aarch64/bits/syscall.h.in   Retargets the four POSIX session/
      process-group syscalls onto the PTY-1a kernel numbers
      (__NR_setsid 89 / __NR_setpgid 90 / __NR_getpgid 91 /
      __NR_getsid 92 -- musl's setsid()/setpgid()/getpgid()/getsid()
      wrappers then work unpatched; the kernel honors the POSIX pid=0
      self sentinel) and appends the three controlling-terminal
      syscall aliases the ioctl dispatcher calls (__NR_tty_acquire 95 /
      __NR_tty_set_fg 96 / __NR_tty_get_fg 97; PTY-1d). After a musl
      re-vendor, extend 0001's awk filter:
          m["setsid"]="89"; m["setpgid"]="90";
          m["getpgid"]="91"; m["getsid"]="92";
      and re-append the tty aliases.

  src/misc/ioctl.c                 FULL REWRITE -- the tty ioctl
      dispatcher, the patch's centerpiece. musl's pty/termios surface
      is entirely ioctl-shaped (isatty = TIOCGWINSZ; unlockpt =
      TIOCSPTLCK; ptsname_r = TIOCGPTN; tcgetattr/tcsetattr =
      TCGETS/TCSETS*; tcgetpgrp/tcsetpgrp = TIOC[GS]PGRP; openpty =
      all of these), so ONE dispatcher makes every upper wrapper work
      unpatched. Translation: termios/winsize <-> the ptyfs ctl file
      /dev/pts/<n>ctl (the PTY-2c five-flag grammar + winsize);
      controlling-terminal ops -> the kernel syscalls 95-97; TIOCGPTN
      -> the fstat qid decode (PTS_FLAG bit 40 | N<<8 | filekind).
      Is-a-pts discrimination = S_ISCHR(st_mode) + the qid decode (the
      ptyfs PTY-3 S_IFCHR posture; load-bearing against /net's bit-40
      CONN_FLAG qids, which report S_IFREG). Unknown requests answer
      ENOTTY (the Linux convention; pre-PTY-3 pouch answered ENOSYS
      for every ioctl). TCFLSH / TIOCGSID / TIOCNOTTY are honest
      ENOTSUP seams; TCSBRK (drain/break) answers 0 on a pts (drain is
      complete-on-return by the synchronous-ring construction).

  src/misc/pty.c                   posix_openpt opens /dev/pts/ptmx --
      the devpts-NATIVE mint node (Linux has the same node; its
      /dev/ptmx is a compat symlink Thylacine cannot provide
      pre-symlinks, G11). The open IS the mint (the Plan 9 clone
      idiom: ptyfs rebinds the opened fid onto a fresh master).
      grantpt (a musl no-op) + unlockpt (TIOCSPTLCK -> dispatcher
      no-op) + ptsname_r (TIOCGPTN) then work unpatched.

  src/misc/openpty.c               The same /dev/pts/ptmx redirect
      (musl's openpty opens the mint node directly, not via
      posix_openpt). Everything else in openpty() is ioctl-shaped and
      works via the dispatcher. O_NOCTTY is inert on Thylacine
      (acquisition is always an explicit TIOCSCTTY; the pouch openat
      maps only O_ACCMODE).

  src/internal/_pouch_signal.h     POUCH_NOTE_BIT_TTY (1u<<5, the
      PTY-1b family bit) + POUCH_NOTE_MASK_SUPPORTED widened to 0x2f
      (bit 4 stays reserved). Doc preamble grows the tty family
      contract: receive-only signums, the SIG_DFL dispositions, and
      the DOCUMENTED SIGTSTP-default seam (below).

  src/signal/_pouch_signal.c       The translation + dispatch growth:
      __pouch_sig_to_note maps SIGQUIT->"tty:quit", SIGTSTP->
      "tty:susp", SIGCONT->"tty:cont", SIGWINCH->"tty:winch",
      SIGHUP->"tty:hup"; the sigset marshalling folds any tty-family
      member onto the ONE kernel family bit (documented coarseness --
      blocking one blocks all five; the kernel terminate-class latch
      makes a masked quit/hup fire on unmask); the bootstrap
      dispatcher routes the five names to their signums and applies
      the SIG_DFL dispositions: quit/hup NDFLT (whole-Proc terminate,
      the POSIX default), winch/cont NCONT (POSIX ignore; a cont's
      RESUME already happened kernel-side at SYS_TTY_CONT),
      susp NCONT-ignore -- the DOCUMENTED v1.0 SEAM: POSIX default is
      STOP, but pouch's always-registered bootstrap makes every pouch
      Proc "caught" to the kernel's pre-delivery stop gate
      (proc_tty_susp_would_stop_locked reads handler_va != 0), and
      the kernel NDFLT arm TERMINATES (exits -> proc_group_terminate,
      never stops), so ^Z on a handler-less pouch program is ignored
      rather than stopping it. NDFLT here would turn ^Z into process
      death -- the one actively-wrong option. The clean fix is a
      kernel NDFLT-stop arm for tty:susp (an ABI-semantics change on
      the audited notes surface -- needs signoff); tracked in
      docs/reference/83-pouch-signals.md.

  src/signal/sigaction.c           The accepted-signum set widens by
      the five tty signums. SIGSTOP stays outside the set (EINVAL --
      uncatchable per POSIX).

  src/signal/kill.c                The tty receive-only gate: the
  src/signal/raise.c               kernel POST axis rejects any
      userspace tty:* post (the PTY-1b round-1 F4 / I-39 gate -- only
      a pts's minting server can originate terminal events, so nobody
      forges a HUP), so kill()/raise() of a tty-family signum answer
      EPERM up front (the POSIX-shaped errno; the kernel would refuse
      with a bare -1 anyway). Handlers CATCH the kernel-raised
      events; sending them is not a thing.

  src/fcntl/openat.c               Resolution moved onto the stalk
      resolver: the 0009 body walked per-component via SYS_walk_open,
      opening EVERY intermediate with the FINAL omode -- structurally
      unable to open a write-mode file through a directory or across a
      mount (the first live instance: posix_openpt's O_RDWR open of
      /dev/pts/ptmx, crossing devramfs -> devdev -> ptyfs; ENOENT).
      Now ONE SYS_open (= 65, stalk-1: per-component X-search +
      mount-crossing inside the resolver; only the FINAL component is
      opened) + the REAL -errno decode (ER-1) where the loop could
      only answer a blanket ENOENT. Every pouch open()/openat() rides
      this (open.c already forwards here, 16b-gamma); the whole
      existing pouch prover ladder + the stratumd boot re-prove the
      old surface in-guest.

  src/misc/pty.c (__ptsname_r)     The raw-SYS_ioctl BYPASS reroutes:
  src/unistd/isatty.c              musl reaches its tty surface two
  src/termios/tcdrain.c            ways -- the public ioctl() (tcgetattr/
  src/termios/tcgetwinsize.c       tcsetattr/tcgetpgrp/tcsetpgrp/
  src/termios/tcsetwinsize.c       unlockpt/openpty) and DIRECT
  src/stdio/__stdout_write.c       __syscall(SYS_ioctl,...) calls, which
  src/stdio/__fdopen.c             on Thylacine hit the 0xFFFF -ENOSYS
      sentinel and BYPASS the dispatcher (ptsname_r returned ENOSYS;
      isatty was constant-0). Each direct caller is rerouted through
      the public ioctl(). The two stdio probes are the line-buffering
      tty detection (fdopen + first stdout write): routing them makes
      a pouch program's stdout LINE-BUFFERED on a pts (the POSIX
      interactive behavior PTY-4's consumers need; one probe per
      stream lifetime), errno-preserved so the common non-tty failure
      cannot clobber a successful stdio write's errno.

Deliberately NOT in this patch:

  - forkpty: structurally dead -- pouch has no fork()/clone()
    (__NR_fork/__NR_clone are the 0xFFFF -ENOSYS sentinel; a
    pre-existing pouch-wide seam, not a pty gap). musl's forkpty
    fails honestly at its fork() call. login_tty likewise depends on
    the unmapped dup3.
  - kill(-pgrp): the kernel SYS_POSTNOTE has no process-group form
    (the PTY-1 design's notes_post_pgrp exists kernel-internally for
    the tty seam only). A negative pid fails the kernel pid lookup
    honestly. The postnote pgrp arm is an ABI addition -- deferred
    with signoff, alongside the NDFLT-stop arm above.
  - getpid() stays unmapped (out of the pty surface; setsid()'s
    return value carries the sid == pid where the probe needs it).

